Document: Visual Shaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/visual_shaders.rst
Summary: This document introduces Visual Shaders in Godot, explaining their purpose and how they differ from text-based shaders.

Visual Shaders are a node-based system for creating shaders in Godot. They allow you to visually construct shader logic by connecting nodes, which can be more intuitive for artists and designers who may not be familiar with shader programming languages like GLSL.

Key Rule: Visual Shaders are compiled into text-based shaders (like GLSL) before being used by the engine. This means they offer the same power and flexibility as text shaders but with a different workflow.

Visual Shaders are particularly useful for:
*   Creating complex visual effects without writing code.
*   Rapid prototyping of shader ideas.
*   Collaborating between programmers and artists, as the visual representation is easily understandable.

While Visual Shaders are powerful, understanding the underlying shader concepts can still be beneficial for advanced usage and debugging.
---CHUNK---
