Document: VisualShaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/visual_shaders.rst
Summary: This document explains how to create and use VisualShaders in Godot, covering the Shader Editor interface and its toolbar options.
VisualShaders can be created in any ShaderMaterial. To start, create a new ``ShaderMaterial`` on an object, then assign a ``Shader`` resource to its ``Shader`` property. Clicking the new ``Shader`` resource will open the Create Shader dialog. Change the Type option to ``VisualShader`` and give it a name.

Clicking the created visual shader opens the Shader Editor. The editor has four main areas: a file list on the left, the upper toolbar, the shader graph itself, and a material preview on the right (which can be toggled).

The toolbar, from left to right, includes:
- An arrow to toggle the visibility of the files panel.
- A ``File`` button with options for saving, loading, and creating files.
- An ``Add Node`` button to open a menu for adding nodes to the graph.
- A drop-down menu for selecting the shader type (Vertex, Fragment, Light), which determines available built-in nodes.
- Buttons and a number input for controlling zoom level, grid snapping, and grid line distance.
- A toggle for the graph minimap in the bottom right.
- A button to automatically arrange selected nodes.
- A ``Manage Varyings`` button to add or remove varyings.
- A button to show the generated shader code from the graph.
- A toggle for the material preview.
- An ``Online Docs`` button to open this documentation.
- A button to detach the shader editor into its own window.

Note: Although VisualShaders don't require coding, they use the same logic as script shaders. Understanding both is recommended for a full grasp of the shading pipeline. The visual shader graph is converted to script shader code behind the scenes, which can be viewed to understand node functionality and how to replicate it in scripts.
---CHUNK---
Document: Visual Shaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/visual_shaders.rst
Summary: This section describes how to use the Visual Shader Editor in Godot, including adding nodes, connecting them, and understanding scalar and vector conversions.

The Visual Shader Editor is used to create shaders visually. A new `VisualShader` starts with an output node, and all node connections terminate at this output node's sockets. Nodes are the fundamental building blocks of shaders.

To add a new node:
- Click the "Add Node" button in the upper-left corner.
- Right-click on an empty area in the graph.

A popup menu will appear. Its properties are:
- If you right-click on the graph, the menu appears at the cursor position, and the new node is created there. Otherwise, it appears at the graph's center.
- The menu can be resized, and its size and content position are saved between uses.
- "Expand All" and "Collapse All" options in the drop-down menu help manage the list of available nodes.
- Nodes can be dragged and dropped from the popup onto the graph.

While nodes are categorized, the menu can initially seem overwhelming. Experiment by adding nodes, connecting them to the output socket, and observing the results.

When connecting nodes:
- Connecting a scalar output to a vector input sets all vector components to the scalar's value.
- Connecting a vector output to a scalar input sets the scalar's value to the average of the vector's components.
---CHUNK---
Document: Visual Shaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/visual_shaders.rst
Summary: Describes the interface of Visual Shader nodes, including input/output ports and their corresponding types and colors.
Visual shader nodes have input and output ports. The input ports are located on the left side of the node, and output ports are located on the right side of the node.

Port types:
* Scalar (Gray): A single value.
* Vector (Purple): A set of values.
* Boolean (Green): On or off, true or false.
* Transform (Pink): A matrix, usually used to transform vertices.
* Sampler (Orange): A texture sampler. It can be used to sample textures.

All of the types are used in the calculations of vertices, fragments, and lights in the shader. For example: matrix multiplication, vector addition, or scalar division. There are other types but these are the main ones.
---CHUNK---
